tive their parents, are cannot learn in an environment where the teachers and school staff are constantly having to focus on the learning and behavioral difficulties of the students who's parents are not supportive, unmotivated, and too distracted, or lazy, to raise their own children and expect the school to do it for them.  No amount of money or &quot;investment&quot; in the public schools is going to change the fact that too many kids are not being parented and are not being taught that you succeed in this world through hard work and discipline.  My kids are grown, thank God, but if they weren't they'd be in a private school no matter how many jobs I had to work to make it happen. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="990" language="en" documentId="2849" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Gail Schuck" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:08PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="2849" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="990"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>